english:
  title: A Reflection on the Record of the Tower of Reclamation
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A certain Scholar Zhao came bearing a record of the Tower of Reclamation, which he showed me, saying: "This record was written by the Hermit of No-Explanation. The tower stands within the Welling Jewel Temple. Men esteem towers and pavilions because they allow one to ascend to heights and gaze upon distant vistas, to set the mind wandering and the eyes roaming free, to exhaust the essence of mountains and rivers, to summon forth wind and moonlight—all to nourish the pleasures of contemplation. Yet what bearing does this have upon learning?" He continued: "Now this tower bears the name 'Reclamation.' What virtue does it draw from being called a tower?"

    I replied: "No, you are mistaken. The sorrow and joy of men spring from the heart and take shape according to the circumstances they encounter. When the heart clings to melancholy, even when meeting the splendor of mountains and waters, the beauty of wind and moon serves only to deepen one's sorrow. The mountains of Lingyang, fairest in all the South, the exile beholds as a prison. The Tower of Yueyang, most magnificent under Heaven, the banished official sees as a cause for tears. Should one lose one's original heart, there exists no place where sadness does not dwell. What joy could any tower bring?

    But if one overcomes selfish desire and recovers the Way of Heaven, then the heart opens like dawn. It becomes vast as Heaven and Earth, harmonious as the myriad things. Boundless and free, it finds joy in all it encounters. Thus there are those who dwell in a simple cottage with a single bowl of rice and a gourd of water, yet their joy remains unchanged—such was the Reclamation of Yan Hui. In sum: only through virtue does one truly savor joy as joy. To name the tower 'Reclamation' is to grasp its very essence.
  footnotes:
    - Yan Hui (顏子) was the foremost disciple of Confucius, famous for his contentment despite extreme poverty. This allusion emphasizes the Confucian ideal of inner virtue transcending external circumstance.
    - The Tower of Yueyang is a celebrated landmark in classical Chinese literature, famously the subject of a melancholy essay by Fan Zhongyan. Its contrast with the serene mountain landscape reinforces the philosophical point about perception being rooted in the observer's inner state rather than objective beauty.
